Interestingly, after calcinating at 550 °C, the luminescence characteristics of the obtained materials (Eu5.5Tb4.5(DPA)n@Lap@550 °C) have remarkable changes, displaying tunable emission light colors from orange to bright purple white under UV light of different wavelengths from 254 to 365 nm (the inset in Fig. 3
                     a). The foregoing results are in good agreement with their corresponding emission spectra. As shown in this emission spectra, apart from the characteristic emission peaks of Tb3+ and Eu3+, strong emission band at 430 nm and 468 nm also emerge (Fig. 3a). Moreover, the relative content of the broad bands at 430 nm and 468 nm, emission peaks of Tb3+ and Eu3+ gradually change along with the excitation wavelength increase from 254 to 365 nm (Table S1), giving rise to the above tunable luminescence colors directly. The CIE values range from (0.35, 0.39) to (0.25, 0.25) with excitation wavelength varying from 254 to 365 nm (shown in Fig. 3b). Notably, upon excitation under 323 nm, the CIE values of Eu5.5Tb4.5(DPA)n@Lap@550 °C is (0.30, 0.34) (Fig. 4
                     ) near the ideal white light (0.33, 0.33), which display appropriate CCT values (7045 K) high CRI (90). When the excitation wavelength was changed to 310 nm, the CIE, CRI and CCT became (0.31, 0.37) (Fig. S8), 86, and 5926 K respectively.
